www.example.com/en/products/shoes/1234 have like?


If you want to make that URL work with a **dynamic route in React (App Router style, like Next.js)**, you’d set up your routing so that parts of the path (`/en/products/shoes/1234`) are treated as parameters.

---

## 🔑 Example in Next.js App Router

### Folder structure
```
app/
  [lang]/
    products/
      [category]/
        [id]/
          page.js
```

### `page.js`
```jsx
export default function ProductPage({ params }) {
  const { lang, category, id } = params;

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Language: {lang}</h1>
      <h2>Category: {category}</h2>
      <p>Product ID: {id}</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

---

### How it works
- URL: `/en/products/shoes/1234`
- `params.lang` → `"en"`
- `params.category` → `"shoes"`
- `params.id` → `"1234"`

So the page dynamically renders based on the path segments.

---

## ⚖️ General React (without Next.js)
If you’re using **React Router**:
```jsx
import { BrowserRouter, Routes, Route, useParams } from "react-router-dom";

function ProductPage() {
  const { lang, category, id } = useParams();
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Language: {lang}</h1>
      <h2>Category: {category}</h2>
      <p>Product ID: {id}</p>
    </div>
  );
}

export default function App() {
  return (
    <BrowserRouter>
      <Routes>
        <Route path="/:lang/products/:category/:id" element={<ProductPage />} />
      </Routes>
    </BrowserRouter>
  );
}
```

---

✨ In short:  
- In **Next.js App Router**, you use folder names like `[lang]`, `[category]`, `[id]`.  
- In **React Router**, you use `:param` in the route path.  

Both approaches let you handle URLs like `www.example.com/en/products/shoes/1234` dynamically.

